    <segment id="1" parent="10" relname="preparation">
That&apos;s a very good observation you made about keyboards P42. </segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="25" relname="span"> In fact, my first 
paper for this class was on keyboards.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="26" relname="span">  I did a study on the comparison between the 
QWERTY and Dvorak keyboards with respect to their usability attributes and HCI issues.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="23" relname="span">   
In so many words, I found that typing fatigue, errors, and slow speed are generally 
caused by bad design in allocating letters among keyboard rows, among fingers, and 
between the left and right hands.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="17" relname="span">  And the QWERTY keyboard (which is what you are 
probably refering to as the standardized keyboard) is designed with most of the common 
key features such as the keypad, delete key, home, page down, etc.. on the right-hand 
side...</segment>
    <segment id="18" parent="4" relname="background">just like you mentioned.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="20" relname="span">  By contrast, the Dvorak keyboard does accommodate the 
left-hand user,</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="5" relname="elaboration"> or at least takes a load off of a person&apos;s right hand,</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="5" relname="concession"> but is not so popular 
of a keyboard.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="7" relname="antithesis">  The QWERTY keyboard has pretty much dominated the market.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="24" relname="span">  There 
are options out there,</segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="21" relname="sequence"> but we just have to look around a little.</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="21" relname="sequence">  And once you find a better 
design,</segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="21" relname="sequence"> you have to re-train yourself,</segment>
    <segment id="15" parent="22" relname="span"> because it&apos;s intuitiveness will probably not seem all 
that great,</segment>
    <segment id="16" parent="15" relname="volitional-cause"> since we are so used to using QWERTY keyboards.</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="27" relname="joint">  Good thread.  </segment>
